card.note: Be prepared to feel overwhelmed. There's a lot going in your life right now. Expect to have moments where it seems a bit too much. As one student says, be prepared to feel completely unprepared. The trick is knowing that you're not the only one feeling that way.
card.author: Aunt Meg

card.note: Don't procrastinate; prioritize your life. It may have been easy in high school to wait until the last minute to complete an assignment and still get a good grade, but that kind of stuff will not work for you in college. Give yourself deadlines -- and stick to them.
card.author: Aunt Meg

card.note: Take advantage of the study resources on campus. Just about all colleges have learning labs and tutors available. If you're having some troubles, these resources are another tool available to you. Another idea: form study groups.
card.author: Aunt Meg

card.note: Find the ideal place for you to study. It may be your dorm room or a cozy corner of the library, but find a place that works best for you to get your work done -- while avoiding as many distractions as possible.
card.author: Aunt Meg

card.note: Make time for you. Be sure you set aside some time and activities that help you relax and take the stress out of your day or week. Whether it's doing an art project, watching your favorite television shows, be good to yourself.
card.author: Aunt Casey

card.note: Go to the Gym. You'll have access to awesome equipment to help fight the freshman fifteen – plus it's a great place to scope out the hotties!
card.author: Aunt Meg

card.note: Your folks will miss you a lot by the time they make their first visit to campus. They'll spoil you by taking you and your friends out to dinner, give them a hug and tell them you love them. It's the perfect opportunity to thank the for all they have done for You.

card.note: Talking to your parents may seem like the last thing you want to do, but they are a great resource for comfort. Call or facetime your Mom. Make a call home schedule and stick to it.

card.note: Get an internship the summer after your sophomore year. You’ll forge professional connections early on and make it easier to get another internship the next summer. Graduating with two under your belt will give you a real leg up on the competition.
